-- COMPLETE: 86 eval-one frames (0-85). 76 cells spawned across 3 fan-out levels.
-- The fractal pattern (decompose → validate → spawn) repeated 4 times, each
-- time expanding the graph by an order of magnitude.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= obs-fractal-self-similarity
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "FRACTAL SELF-SIMILARITY: the pattern decompose → validate → spawn repeats identically at all 4 levels. Level 1: decompose-goal → validate-level-1 → spawn-task-decomposers. Level 2: task-decomposer-* → validate-level-2 → spawn-step-decomposers. Level 3: step-decomposer-* → validate-level-3 → spawn-action-decomposers. Level 4: action-decomposer-* → validate-level-4 → assemble. Same structure, different granularity. Cell's ⊢⊢ spawner makes each level's fan-out STRUCTURAL — new cells join the graph. The fractal is in the TOPOLOGY, not just the content."

⊢= obs-oracle-at-every-level
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ORACLE GATES PREVENT GARBAGE PROPAGATION: each level has a validate cell that checks MECE (mutually exclusive, collectively exhaustive). If validate-level-1 returned valid=false, the ⊨? would trigger a retry of decompose-goal — the garbage would NOT propagate to Level 2. This is the key advantage over flat decomposition: errors caught early don't multiply. In this execution, all 4 oracles passed on the first try — the ⊥ paths were never exercised. A more ambiguous goal ('make something useful') would trigger retries."

⊢= obs-exponential-fan-out
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "EXPONENTIAL GROWTH IS CONTROLLED: 1 goal → 4 sub-goals → 15 tasks → 57 steps → 170 actions. Growth factors: 4x, 3.75x, 3.8x, ~3x. Roughly 3-4x at each level. 4 levels of 4x = 256 theoretical max. Actual: 170 (variance because some tasks decompose into 3, others into 5). Cell's max bound on ⊢⊢ (max 5, max 20, max 60) prevents runaway growth. Without these bounds, a poorly-calibrated decomposer could spawn thousands of cells. The bounds are the HALTING mechanism for fractal programs."

⊢= obs-cross-cutting-dependencies
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "CROSS-CUTTING DEPENDENCIES EMERGE AT VALIDATION: validate-level-2 found that T4.2 (onboarding) depends on T1.2 (invoice API) and T3.2 (plans) — these are in DIFFERENT sub-goals. A naive MECE decomposition misses cross-subgoal dependencies because it only checks within each sub-goal. The cross-cutting validator catches what the decomposers can't see. This is Cell's DAG structure at work: dependencies BETWEEN cells are first-class, not just dependencies WITHIN cells. The validator reads outputs from ALL task-decomposers simultaneously."

⊢= obs-hours-as-convergence-metric
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ESTIMATED HOURS VALIDATE FEASIBILITY TOP-DOWN: validate-level-3 summed 244 hours from all 15 task estimates. This is within the 480-hour budget (3 months × 1 person). If the sum had exceeded 480, the oracle would fail → retry decomposition with tighter scope. The hours metric acts as a CONVERGENCE CHECK: does the plan fit reality? This is something a pure recursive decomposition can't do — you need the AGGREGATE view across all leaves to check feasibility. Cell's collect-from-all pattern (given step-decomposer-*→estimated-hours) makes this natural."

⊢= obs-no-retries-needed
  given §11-fractal-task-planner
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "NO ⊥ TRIGGERED — THE HAPPY PATH: all 4 validation oracles passed on the first try. This means the ⊨? retry paths were never exercised. The program STRUCTURE supports retries (each validate has ⊨? on failure: retry max 2) but the EXECUTION didn't need them. This is both a strength (clean decomposition) and a weakness of this trace (the most interesting Cell behavior — oracle failure → retry → ⊥ — wasn't demonstrated). A more adversarial goal or stricter oracles would force the retry paths. The fractal's real power shows when Level 3 says 'these steps are too vague' and forces Level 2 to re-decompose."
